"# Appendix K — Music: Composition Deep Dive

Chapter 16 taught the hardware — how `note`, `chord`, `synth/kit`, and the composer's voice pool fit together. This appendix teaches what to *do* with them. Music theory isn't a prerequisite to programming music; it's a set of shortcuts other people found for making sequences of notes that the ear enjoys. This appendix hands you the shortcuts.

Every example verified against the CLI. Every example runs headless — the audio driver may or may not produce sound depending on your platform, but every note sequence completes cleanly. If you're on macOS with `afplay`, you'll hear it. If not, you'll see the sequence print. Either way, the *shape* of the music is what matters, and the shape is deterministic.

Also see: `~/code/motoi-scheme/carts/cart-maker-3-music/` for five ready-to-run cart-shaped versions of these ideas (twinkle-melody, drum-loop, arpeggio, chord-progression, layered-song).

## K.1 The C major scale

The most-taught scale in Western music. Seven notes plus the octave. On a piano, all white keys. The intervals go **whole-whole-half-whole-whole-whole-half** — remember that pattern and you can build a major scale starting on any note. C major is convenient because it needs no sharps or flats.

```scheme
(define BPM  120)
(define Q    (/ 60.0 BPM))   ; quarter-note in seconds
(define VEL  0.6)

(define c-major-up   (list 'C4 'D4 'E4 'F4 'G4 'A4 'B4 'C5))
(define c-major-down (list 'C5 'B4 'A4 'G4 'F4 'E4 'D4 'C4))

(define (play-scale label notes)
  (display label) (newline)
  (for-each (lambda (p) (note p Q VEL)) notes))

(display \"C major scale\") (newline)
(display \"=============\") (newline)
(play-scale \"  ascending \"  c-major-up)
(play-scale \"  descending\" c-major-down)
(newline)
(display \"music-1 done: 16 notes.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** Do-re-mi-fa-so-la-ti-do up. Do-ti-la-so-fa-mi-re-do down. The sound of every music class you ever sat through.

## K.2 Minor and pentatonic scales

Same range, three flavors. **A natural minor** shares its pitches with C major but starts on A — the same notes, a different mood. **Minor pentatonic** drops the 2nd and 6th degrees, leaving five notes that never clash with each other, which is why it's the scale that guitar solos live in. **Major pentatonic** does the same trick over a major root.

```scheme
(define BPM  120)
(define Q    (/ 60.0 BPM))
(define VEL  0.55)

(define a-minor       (list 'A3 'B3 'C4 'D4 'E4 'F4 'G4 'A4))
(define a-min-pent    (list 'A3 'C4 'D4 'E4 'G4 'A4))
(define c-maj-pent    (list 'C4 'D4 'E4 'G4 'A4 'C5))

(define (play label notes)
  (display \"  \") (display label) (display \"  (\") (display (length notes))
  (display \" notes)\") (newline)
  (for-each (lambda (p) (note p Q VEL)) notes))

(display \"Three scales, same root region:\") (newline)
(play \"A natural minor\" a-minor)
(play \"A minor pentatonic\" a-min-pent)
(play \"C major pentatonic\" c-maj-pent)
(newline)
(display \"music-2 done: 20 notes across 3 scales.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** Minor sounds serious. Minor pentatonic sounds bluesy. Major pentatonic sounds happy and folksy. Same seven-ish notes, three moods.

## K.3 Chord voicings

A chord is a set of pitch *classes* — C major is always C+E+G, regardless of octave. But *how* you stack those pitches changes how the chord feels. **Root position** puts the root at the bottom. **First inversion** puts the third at the bottom. **Open voicing** spreads the chord across more than an octave — that's the piano-teacher recipe for a big-sounding chord.

```scheme
(define HIT 0.6)
(define VEL 0.5)

(define root-position    (list 'C4 'E4 'G4))            ; 1-3-5
(define first-inversion  (list 'E4 'G4 'C5))            ; 3-5-1
(define open-voicing     (list 'C3 'G3 'E4 'C5))        ; wide, 'piano' feel

(define (strike label voicing)
  (display \"  \") (display label) (display \": \") (display voicing) (newline)
  (chord voicing HIT VEL))

(display \"C major, three voicings\") (newline)
(display \"=======================\") (newline)
(strike \"root position    \" root-position)
(strike \"first inversion  \" first-inversion)
(strike \"open voicing     \" open-voicing)
(newline)
(display \"music-3 done: 3 chords, 10 voices mixed.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** All three are C major. The root position is tight and unambiguous. The inversion feels like it wants to move to a resolving F. The open voicing feels bigger — like a whole band playing one chord instead of a piano. Same notes. Different geometry.

## K.4 Arpeggio patterns

An arpeggio walks the notes of a chord one at a time. Same pitches as `chord`, but sequential. Three canonical shapes: **straight up** (root-3rd-5th-octave), **up-down** (Baroque figuration, the shape Bach used for filler), and **Alberti bass** (root-5th-3rd-5th, an 18th-century left-hand pattern that shows up everywhere from Mozart to modern pop).

```scheme
(define BPM  120)
(define STEP (/ 60.0 BPM 4))    ; 16th note
(define VEL  0.5)

(define straight-up   (list 'C4 'E4 'G4 'C5))
(define up-down       (list 'C4 'E4 'G4 'C5 'G4 'E4))
(define alberti       (list 'C4 'G4 'E4 'G4 'C4 'G4 'E4 'G4))

(define (play label notes)
  (display \"  \") (display label) (newline)
  (for-each (lambda (p) (note p STEP VEL)) notes))

(display \"Arpeggio patterns on C major\") (newline)
(display \"============================\") (newline)
(play \"straight up  (1-3-5-8)   \" straight-up)
(play \"up-down      (Baroque)   \" up-down)
(play \"Alberti bass (1-5-3-5)   \" alberti)
(newline)
(display \"music-4 done: 18 arpeggiated notes.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** The same C major chord broken up three ways. The Alberti pattern is especially useful because it fills time without demanding attention — perfect for accompaniment.

## K.5 A minor-pentatonic riff

Riffs are the melodic hooks you hum in the shower. Most rock and pop riffs live in a minor pentatonic scale of some key. This one is a two-bar A-minor-pentatonic figure that repeats — the shape of every bass line you've ever heard.

```scheme
(define BPM  100)
(define E    (/ 60.0 BPM 2))    ; eighth-note
(define VEL  0.6)

(define bar-1 (list 'A2 'C3 'D3 'E3 'D3 'C3 'A2))
(define bar-2 (list 'A2 'C3 'D3 'G3 'E3 'D3 'A2))

(define (play-bar label notes)
  (display label) (newline)
  (for-each (lambda (p) (note p E VEL)) notes))

(display \"Two-bar riff (A minor pentatonic)\") (newline)
(display \"=================================\") (newline)
(play-bar \"bar 1\" bar-1)
(play-bar \"bar 2\" bar-2)
(play-bar \"bar 3 (repeat 1)\" bar-1)
(play-bar \"bar 4 (repeat 2)\" bar-2)
(newline)
(display \"music-5 done: 4-bar riff, 28 notes.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** Down-up-down-up on the low strings of an imaginary bass. The two-bar unit gives it more interest than one-bar-repeated would; that's a compositional trick worth stealing.

## K.6 The backbeat drum pattern

The most-used drum pattern in Western music. Kick on beats 1 and 3, snare on 2 and 4, hats on every 8th note. Also paints a visual grid of the pattern so you can see it while it plays.

```scheme
(define BARS 2)

(define kick-pat  '(#t #f #f #f #t #f #f #f))
(define snare-pat '(#f #f #t #f #f #f #t #f))
(define hat-pat   '(#t #t #t #t #t #t #t #t))

(define (paint-pattern)
  (clear)
  (begin-frame)
  (set-color 'black)
  (rect-fill 0 0 80 30)
  (set-color 'red)
  (let loop ((i 0))
    (if (< i 8)
        (begin
          (if (list-ref kick-pat i)
              (rectangle (* i 10) 0 10 10))    ; alias rectangle (outline)
          (loop (+ i 1)))))
  (set-color 'yellow)
  (let loop ((i 0))
    (if (< i 8)
        (begin
          (if (list-ref snare-pat i)
              (fill-rect (* i 10) 10 10 10))   ; alias fill-rect
          (loop (+ i 1)))))
  (set-color 'cyan)
  (let loop ((i 0))
    (if (< i 8)
        (begin
          (if (list-ref hat-pat i)
              (pixel (+ (* i 10) 5) 25))       ; alias pixel
          (loop (+ i 1)))))
  (end-frame)
  (render))

(define (play-step i)
  (if (list-ref kick-pat i)  (synth/kit 'kick  i))
  (if (list-ref snare-pat i) (synth/kit 'snare i))
  (if (list-ref hat-pat i)   (synth/kit 'hat   i)))

(paint-pattern)
(let loop ((bar 0))
  (if (< bar BARS)
      (begin
        (display \"bar \") (display (+ bar 1)) (newline)
        (let inner ((i 0))
          (if (< i 8)
              (begin (play-step i) (inner (+ i 1)))))
        (loop (+ bar 1)))))
(display \"music-6 done: 2 bars of the classic backbeat + grid painted.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear + see.** *boom-tick-CRASH-tick-boom-tick-CRASH-tick*. Three rows on the framebuffer show which step of the bar each drum fires on: red outlines for kicks, yellow filled squares for snares, cyan pixels for hats.

## K.7 The I-IV-V-I progression in three keys

Almost every blues and country song, half of pop, most of hymns: this progression. **I**, the tonic. **IV**, the sub-dominant. **V**, the dominant. Back to **I**. Move the same progression to three different keys — C, G, D — to see that the *function* of each chord doesn't depend on where the key starts.

```scheme
(define HIT 0.7)
(define VEL 0.55)

(define C-major (list (list 'C4 'E4 'G4)
                      (list 'F4 'A4 'C5)
                      (list 'G4 'B4 'D5)
                      (list 'C4 'E4 'G4)))
(define G-major (list (list 'G3 'B3 'D4)
                      (list 'C4 'E4 'G4)
                      (list 'D4 'F#4 'A4)
                      (list 'G3 'B3 'D4)))
(define D-major (list (list 'D3 'F#3 'A3)
                      (list 'G3 'B3 'D4)
                      (list 'A3 'C#4 'E4)
                      (list 'D3 'F#3 'A3)))

(define (play-prog label chords)
  (display \"  \") (display label) (newline)
  (for-each
    (lambda (voicing)
      (display \"    \") (display voicing) (newline)
      (chord voicing HIT VEL))
    chords))

(display \"I-IV-V-I in three keys\") (newline)
(display \"======================\") (newline)
(play-prog \"in C\" C-major)
(play-prog \"in G\" G-major)
(play-prog \"in D\" D-major)
(newline)
(display \"music-7 done: 12 chords, 36 voices mixed.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** The same *feeling* three times in three keys. C sounds low and grounded. G sounds warm. D sounds bright and open. Same shape, different room.

## K.8 A layered piece

Melody + bass + drums, walked bar-at-a-time. Declares the tempo via `song/config` so the composer knows the BPM. This is a compressed version of the pattern in Cart Maker 3's `layered-song.scm`.

```scheme
(define BPM 96)
(define E   (/ 60.0 BPM 2))

(define cfg (song/config :voices 8 :voice-steal 'oldest :bpm BPM))
(display \"song/config -> \") (display cfg) (newline)

(define (bar n)
  (display \"bar \") (display n) (newline)
  ;; beat 1
  (synth/kit 'kick)
  (synth/kit 'hat)
  (note 'C3 E 0.55)
  (note 'C5 E 0.5)
  ;; beat 3
  (synth/kit 'hat)
  (note 'E5 E 0.5)
  ;; beat 5
  (synth/kit 'snare)
  (synth/kit 'hat)
  (note 'G3 E 0.55)
  (note 'G5 E 0.5)
  ;; beat 7
  (synth/kit 'hat)
  (note 'E5 E 0.5))

(display \"A layered one-bar cell, played twice.\") (newline)
(bar 1)
(bar 2)

(chord (list 'C4 'E4 'G4 'C5) (* 2 E) 0.5)
(display \"music-8 done: 2 bars + closing C major chord.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** A skeletal groove — kick and hats on the beat, bass moving between C and G on the strong beats, melody floating a C-E-G-E figure on top. Closes with a C major chord ringing.

## K.9 Voice pools and voice/compose

The composer's voice pool is Motoi's polyphony bank. Assign instruments to voices, tell voice 16 (the mixer) which voices to sum, and `composer/emit` round-trips the whole shape back to a Scheme form. This is the substrate under any longer piece.

```scheme
(define pool
  (composer/voice-pool :bind '(demo :pool) :steal 'oldest))

(define stage
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(demo))
    pool))

(composer/voice-assign pool 1 (list :instrument 'lead   :pitch 'C4))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 (list :instrument 'bass   :pitch 'C3))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 (list :instrument 'kick))
(composer/voice-assign pool 4 (list :instrument 'hat))

(composer/voice-mix-set pool (list 1 2 3 4))

(define mix (voice/compose (list 1 2 3 4) 0.7))
(display \"voice/compose -> \") (display mix) (newline)

(display \"composer/emit -> \") (display (composer/emit stage)) (newline)

(note 'C4 0.15 0.5)
(note 'E4 0.15 0.5)
(note 'G4 0.15 0.5)
(note 'C3 0.30 0.6)
(synth/kit 'kick)
(synth/kit 'hat)
(synth/kit 'kick)
(synth/kit 'hat)

(display \"music-9 done: voice pool + emit + short 4-voice demo.\")
(newline)
```

**What you see + hear.** The composer prints the whole voice-pool as a Scheme s-expression — this is what SLAT-canonical means for music: the piece is data, not a black box. Then it plays a short arpeggio and two kick-hat pairs to prove the voices actually route to the audio driver.

## K.10 The 50s progression, fully composed

C-Am-F-G. The chord progression that made pop music. Underneath: the whole triad rings. On top: a four-note melody per chord that outlines each chord's tones. Ends with a bar of backbeat drums.

```scheme
(define BPM 100)
(define Q   (/ 60.0 BPM))
(define H   (* 2 Q))
(define VEL 0.5)

(define I   (list 'C4 'E4 'G4))
(define vi  (list 'A3 'C4 'E4))
(define IV  (list 'F3 'A3 'C4))
(define V   (list 'G3 'B3 'D4))

(define mel-C  (list 'G4 'E4 'C5 'G4))
(define mel-Am (list 'E4 'A4 'C5 'A4))
(define mel-F  (list 'F4 'A4 'C5 'A4))
(define mel-G  (list 'G4 'B4 'D5 'B4))

(define (verse label c mel)
  (display label) (newline)
  (chord c H VEL)
  (for-each
    (lambda (p) (note p Q VEL))
    mel))

(display \"The 50s progression: C - Am - F - G\") (newline)
(display \"====================================\") (newline)
(verse \"  C  (I) \"  I  mel-C)
(verse \"  Am (vi)\" vi mel-Am)
(verse \"  F  (IV)\" IV mel-F)
(verse \"  G  (V) \"  V  mel-G)
(newline)

(display \"one bar of backbeat:\") (newline)
(synth/kit 'kick)  (synth/kit 'hat)
(synth/kit 'hat)
(synth/kit 'snare) (synth/kit 'hat)
(synth/kit 'hat)

(newline)
(display \"music-10 done: full 4-chord progression with melody + drums.\")
(newline)
```

**What you hear.** The changes that Buddy Holly and the Everly Brothers wrote a generation on. Four chords, one melody outlining each, a bar of drums under. That's a whole verse of a whole song.

## The tempo math you actually need

Every example computes durations from BPM the same way:

```scheme
(define BPM  120)
(define Q    (/ 60.0 BPM))         ; quarter note in seconds
(define E    (/ 60.0 BPM 2))       ; eighth note
(define S    (/ 60.0 BPM 4))       ; sixteenth note
(define H    (* 2 Q))              ; half note
(define W    (* 4 Q))              ; whole note
```

That's it. If you can compute one duration you can compute all of them. The rest of composition is deciding *which* note goes *when*.

## Where to go next

- Chapter 16 in this book is your prose companion — this appendix is the runnable-example glossary to it.
- `~/code/motoi-scheme/carts/cart-maker-3-music/` has the five source carts these examples were compressed from.
- The Motoi Book of Composition (a separate book) goes deeper on scales, modes, and the theory under the shortcuts.
- If you want to hear more than headless can give you: run the CLI on macOS and Motoi will route through `afplay` for real audio.
